1274","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1404":"1404","1315":"1315","1423":"1423","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","about 1315":"circa 1315","1364":"1364","1353":"1353","about 1355":"circa 1355","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England"},"en":{"about 1315–":"about 1315–Deceased","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1364–Female":"1364–Deceased","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1370–1404":"1370–1404","–1364":"–1364","1270–1353":"1270–1353","1274–Female":"1274–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1274":"1274","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1404":"1404","1315":"1315","1423":"1423","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","about 1315":"about 1315","1364":"1364","1353":"1353","about 1355":"about 1355","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Trumpington, Cambridgeshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":67,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Fulbourn was born about 1315, in Cambridgeshire, England, her father, Giles de Fulbourne, was 46 and her mother, Unkown Fullbourn, was 42. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with John Reynell."},"et":{"about 1315–":"umbes 1315–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1280–1364":"1280–1364","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1364–Female":"1364–Surnud","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1370–1404":"1370–1404","–1364":"–1364","1270–1353":"1270–1353","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","about 1370":"um